description.text: customized with 3D Slash!

OpenSCAD deltoidal icositetrahedron tile with holes for magnets.

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deltoidal_icositetrahedron

You'll need to print a total of 24 tiles, and 4 disc magnets per tile (axially magnetized). That's 96 magnets in total. I bought mine on eBay in bulk and used superglue to secure them in the tiles.

See the User Defined Variables section of the OpenSCAD script for the parameters you may want to change (magnet holes and overall size of tile, total 4 parameters). Or just use the pre-built STL with 6mm diameter magnets.

Not familiar with OpenSCAD? It is easy to obtain and use! Download it here: http://www.openscad.org. After installation, open up the OpenSCAD file for this thing and hit F6 to render (or use the menu options up top). File->Export as STL and take it to your slicer!

These are also on github: https://github.com/eshira/polyhedra

Magnet Orientations

Opposite sides have the same polarities facing out.
Adjacent sides have opposite polarities facing out.

For example, you could go around the tile starting at any face and go North - South - North - South. Make sure all tiles have identical magnet alignment!!! A good way to keep track is to make your first tile according to the rules above, and use it as a references for every subsequent tile (test your magnets against it).

title: BMW 335i exhaust valve vacuum hose plug I.E. Golf Tee Fix

description.text:
Eventually, the vacuum-operated exhaust valve in BMWs with sport exhausts will go bad. They start to rattle at startup, and then later they cause nasty, loud, flatulent sounds at 3000+ RPM --- just imagine a cross between a whoopy cushion and glass-pack mufflers...this is not a great sound. The official fix is to have the entire valve replaced. But, since that is expensive and welded into the muffler, it's often not worth it. The exhaust in my 335i is still in great shape, so there is no point in replacing it just yet, either. If your exhaust valve is still in good condition but you want to annoy the neighbors a bit more, this makes the exhaust a bit louder below 3000 rpms. They probably already hate you anyway.

This is a variation of the Golf Tee Fix, which involves disconnecting the vacuum hose which goes to the exhaust valve and plugging it with a golf tee. You then shove the offending hose somewhere out of the way. I'm not a golfer, and I refuse to buy a bag of tees for this application. Also, there really isn't a good place to shove the vacuum hose once it's plugged. And finally...a golf tee....really?

This object solves all of those problems. You plug the vacuum hose onto the post on one side of the part. You then slide the part over the hose nipple on the vacuum valve and zip tie it into place. The hose has the exact same routing as before, and it's pretty easy to remove if you ever need to make a trip to the dealership.

title: Rostock Mini Acrylic Plans for Mounted Duet 0.8.5

description.text:
Updated the DXF files provided by Brian Evans for the original Rostock Mini design to include hole for mounting the 100mm by 123mm Duet 0.8.5 printer board. Also took time to add slots for passing through my printers FSR wiring for auto-calibration and decided to replicate the mounting holes along the edge to the remaining two sides of the bed. This should allow the creation of outward facing side panels for the base in the future.

For the top, I pushed the squares for the zip-ties to the outer edge to try to better "round out" the wiring from the end stops. Finally, I mirrored the holes for the motor mounts from the base to one corner of the top for a future extruder motor bracket.

Overall I am happy with the results, but if I had to do it again, I would have doubled the holes on the edge of the base for 3D printing two sets of side panels per side instead of just repeating the 2 holes from the Duet mount. One side panel would be borderline to long as it is currently laid out. I also should have kept the second set of zip-tie squares on the edge of the base for securing the hotend wiring, which is presently crammed in with the endstop wiring.

Printer:

BOSS 1416 Laser Engraver

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Notes:

Using a BOSS 1416 laser cutter with a 60W laser, it took approximately 6 minutes to cut the base and 4 minutes to cut the top out of two sheets of 12" x 12" x 0.236" (~5mm) cast acrylic.

Multiple cuts were needed as we were experimenting with settings and came up with 60% at 5mm/sec for the base. Still needed a second pass when cutting the top, so consider increasing to 65% to 75% power.

I had access to Adobe Illustrator CC through work that I was able to install on my home computer and use to import / open Brian Evan's original frame.dxf file (included with the files) before saving as a CC Illustrator file (*.ai).

After making my adjustments and edits, separating the base and top, setting the stroke to 0.25pt, I then exported the file as an R13/LT95 DXF file. That seemed to work great for laser cutting.

This is a 3D model of a Campanian Askos, a pottery vessel dating back to approximately 4th Century BC, from the collection of the Museum of Applied Arts and Sciences. The Greek word ‘Askos’ refers to the animal-skin bags that were used to carry wine. This Askos was painted black and has original finger print marks around its rim.

This was one of ten Museum objects scanned in 3D for Hack the Collection, a public program in the 2014 Sydney Design Festival, which matched ten contemporary Sydney designers with ten objects from the Museum’s collection.

Designers spent two intensive days in the Festival FabLab, creatively manipulating the 3D object files to design their own hacked interpretations in full view of an excited public. At the conclusion of the weekend, the designers’ remixed objects were 3D printed on MakerBots and displayed alongside their original counterpart.

title: Flexion Extruder Adapter for Robo3D and 80mm X Carriages

description.text:
This is a Flexion mounting option for anyone that owns a Robo3D or similar 80mm rod spacing horizontal x axis. It has mounts for a 50mm Blower fan and a BLTouch Probe for auto leveling.

The Flexion is an incredible extruder designed by the guy who brought you Ninjaflex and is capable of effortlessly printing TPU material as well as easily handing non exotic filaments like PLA without the need to switch between extruder setups.

We HIGHLY recommend you upgrade if you wish to print without repeated failures and inferior quality. Buy one while they are still in stock. They have been selling out the second they get more in: https://flexionextruder.com/

Note that the Flexion kit is technically an upgrade kit for people that have MK style extruders already (which if you have a Robo3d, you do not).

Besides printing these parts and the Flexion kit you will need a couple things:

  • 1x 40mm Fan
  • 1x Fan Heatsink (http://www.ebay.com/itm/262055733096?_trksid=p2057872.m2749.l2649&ssPageName=STRK%3AMEBIDX%3AIT)
  • 2x M3 x 45mm Screw (Might need a #6 washer as well)
  • 4x M3 x 35mm Screw
  • 4x Zip-Ties

Optional

  • 50mm Blower Fan w/ 1x M3 x 20mm Screw & 1 M3 Nut
  • BLTouch Probe w/ 2x M3x10mm Screw & 2x M3 Nuts (http://www.ebay.com/itm/New-BLTouch-Auto-Bed-Leveling-Sensor-To-be-a-Premium-3D-Printer-/201548081668?hash=item2eed33aa04:g:yKIAAOSwa-dWsYvI)

Print Part 1 in ABS or PETG since it will be fairly close to the nozzle. Part 2 and the probe bracket can be printed out of PLA if desired.

Assembly;

  • Place 2x LM8UU bearings into Part 1 and secure them with 2 Zip-ties
  • Using the 2x M3x45mm screws connect in this order.. Part 1 > 40mm Fan > Fan Heatsink > Flexion Mount > NEMA 17 Motor
    -Insert the nut inside the nut trap for the blower mount in Part 2
  • Carefully remove the 4x M3 screws in the back of your NEMA 17 motor.
  • Using the 4x M3x 35mm screws connect Part 2 to the back of your NEMA 17 motor.
  • Attach your belt (You will need to reverse your X-Motor direction since the belt is now backwards. The easiest way is to simply unplug the motor cable and flip it 180 degrees and plug it back in)
  • Print at high speeds in exotic material without living on the edge!

If you wish to install the blower mount and/or BLtouch sensor simply attach them with the previously mentioned screws.

With the BLTouch Probe Mount installed there is a nice channel along the motor to route the wires through along with a clip at top of Part 2 to collect all of them neatly.

***Please note we will be updating this mount over the next week or 2 and adding some more pictures. We still need to add the air re director for the 50mm Blower fan and make some other minor adjustments. If anyone has any questions or suggestions, comment away :) ...

I need something for my wood chipper to turn off the motor in an emergency or quickly turn it off.

So it is 4 pieces the body or the box, the top, the plunger switch, and the plunger stop to keep it from coming out of the casing.

There is a hole in the plunger on the bottom, and the plunger stop for a self tapping flat headed screw press the them together after inserting the plunger through the top.

This is setup to use a dip switch as the electrical, there are no holes for the wiring just for you can drill it wherever you want. the plunger sits loose so i put some blue painters tape on the plunger to give it some friction to hold it in place, if you want to leave it loose you can also use this a buzzer button like on a gameshow.

I wrapped it in aluminum foil tape that i got from the 99c only store to help keep it water tight and help with any heat.

If any one wants me to change what kind of switch or you want to do it your self let me know and ill upload the sketchup file.

Nexus 6p Charging Dock

A simple, dock with a nice snug fit for the Nexus 6P and OEM charging cable.
The crossbar in the back prevents the cable from flipping the whole thing over.
Never mind those holes in the back. They're a vestigial remnant from a failed attempt at a cable lock. :)

The curved shape in the back of this dock serves to minimize volume (for faster printing), and also makes it easy to pick the whole thing up and type while the phone is still docked.

Note: This dock is designed for a snug fit with a naked phone. It will not fit with any sort of case or screen cover.

  • Slicer: Cura Lulzbot edition 19.2

  • Temps: nozzle: 235C, bed: 85C
  • Speed: 45mm/s

This model was built using 123Design.

I started with a rough model of the 6p and OEM USB C cable.
Next, I arranged these models and aligned them to fit one another. Then, using an isometric view, I drew a 2d spline with a pleasing shape for the dock that fit around both phone and cable. Since I wanted to minimize the amount of material used, I created an alternate profile for the middle of the dock to reduce the volume. To create the 3d shape, I copied these profiles and arranged them symmetrically in the appropriate position relative to the phone, and used the "loft" tool to smoothly fill in the 3d shape bounded by the 3d profiles. I then used Meshmixer to double check the stability, to make sure the dock would not tip over when the phone is pressed down into it. Finally, I subtracted the phone and USB cable models from the resulting shape, and scaled up the whole thing by 1% to allow for a good fit.

description.text:
The original design for this comes from the RepRapPro github here: https://github.com/reprappro/Huxley/blob/master/Print-Huxley/Individual-STLs/optional-fan-mount-1off.stl
The idea is a big improvement, (in my view), on other designs I have used which attach fan(s) to the Z carriage as these tend to be too far away from from the part being printed.
There were a number of Huxley's fitted with ducted cooling fans at the recent TCT Personalize show in Birmingham UK on the RepRapPro stand so I printed one!
In the RRP design, the fan is held in place by pushing it over two lugs or prongs which stick out from the face of the fan mount. I understand that the reason for this is to reduce the amount of hardware to the minimum.
However, it might be down to my clumsiness but when fitting a fan to the RRP design, I ended up snapping one of the lugs. This led to my amended design which uses a pair of captive nuts and a couple of 16mm M3 screws.

Print and then push fit two M3 nuts into the holes on the side. As these holes are printed at an angle, you may need to clean up your print and remove some of the layer edges inside the holes using a small file. An alternative is to use half M3 nuts which go in easily.
The ducted fan mount then fixes to the X carriage using two screws. Depending on when you built your Huxley, this may mean printing a different X carriage - you can find the STLs on the RRP Github if needs be.
Attach the fan using 16mm M3 screws. (The fan is the same sort as that used to cool the hot end).

title: FF creator pro door magnet support

description.text:
Simple support for a 8x8x4 mm magnet. The goal is to attach this to the existing chassis screws on the left (and right) hand side.
By gluing a similar magnet on the plexi door itself, the door closes nicely.

(Updated the design to simplify the object and allow the magnet to sit farther from the door a little bit more)

This thing was made with Tinkercad.

Printer:

FlashForge Creator Pro

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2mm or better

Notes:

You might want to use supports for the holes (I did).
If you use rafts, make sure they are not too close to the object. As this is pretty thin, you do not want to damage it while removing the rafts.

• Adapt the object on the static nut inside the machine. You should have something like 2 mms of the bolt sticking out. That is enough to use a spare nut to tighten the object,
  • Then stick the magnet into place, test with the other magnet (for the door), and decide how deep you need to push the first magnet into its hole,
  • Mark where you need to put the magnet on the door, and glue it. I used loctite, one small drop is way too much as both surfaces are flat, you need a very very small quantity,
  • Check if you need to glue the other magnet (in the hole). In my case it was not necessary (I just forcefully pushed it),
  • Repeat for the other side if you see fit (I did it because my printer's door was not really aligned with machine's chassis, but your mileage may vary).

If you use some filament other than black, I recommend painting inside of the googles to black. When I used white filament, it was too transparent. Sunlight was getting through, making it hard to see on the display.

description.text:

This simple clock is stateless - it does not require to set time manually and do not have battery inside to keep time clocking while there is no power supplied. Clock take time instantly on power ON and sync it every 8 hours. Also clock act as light sensor and temperature sensor. See one photo on how sensors looks like inside vera and one photo on how it looks like inside smartphone.
Small demo is here http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-3a9ePBjax8. Clock is installed in a bathroom and powered from the sane wire as a light etc. do not need continuous power like any other clock needs but at the same time it will win any wall or battery clock because of instant sync.
Discussion is here http://forum.mysensors.org/topic/1002/simple-mysensors-clock/2
Take care on a right positioning before slicing and you will not need a support.
